Objectives

1. List the features of ES6
ES6 (ECMAScript 2015) introduced several new JavaScript features, including:
let and const
Arrow functions (=>)
Classes
Class inheritance
Template literals
Destructuring
Spread (...) and Rest operators
Modules (import and export)
Promises
map() and set()

2. Explain JavaScript let
let is used to declare variables with block scope. Its value can be changed, but it cannot be redeclared within the same block.
Example:
let age = 20;
age = 21;

3. Identify the differences between var and let
var	let
Function scoped	Block scoped
Can be redeclared	Cannot be redeclared in the same scope
Can be updated	Can be updated
Hoisted and initialized as undefined	Hoisted but cannot be used before declaration

4. Explain JavaScript const
const is used to declare variables whose value cannot be reassigned after initialization. It is also block scoped.
Example:
const PI = 3.14;

5. Explain ES6 class fundamentals
ES6 classes provide a cleaner syntax to create objects using constructors and methods.
Example:

class Player {
  constructor(name) {
    this.name = name;
  }
}

6. Explain ES6 class inheritance
Inheritance allows one class to inherit properties and methods from another class using the extends keyword.
Example:
class Player {
  constructor(name) {
    this.name = name;
  }
}

class Captain extends Player {
}

7. Define ES6 arrow functions
Arrow functions are a shorter way of writing functions and automatically inherit the surrounding this value.
Example:
const add = (a, b) => a + b;

8. Identify Set() and Map()
Set
A Set stores unique values.
Example:
const numbers = new Set([1, 2, 2, 3]);
// Output: 1, 2, 3
Map
A Map stores key-value pairs.
Example:
const student = new Map();
student.set("Name", "John");
student.set("Age", 20);

